  "editorial": {
    "title": "Count Subarrays with Given Sum",
    "intuition": "The problem requires counting the number of subarrays within the given array that sum up to a target value k. A straightforward approach is to consider all possible subarrays and calculate their sums, checking if any match the target sum.",
    "bruteForce": "The brute force solution iterates over all possible subarrays, calculates their sums, and increments a counter whenever it finds a match. This approach is correct but inefficient due to its quadratic time complexity, resulting from the nested loops used to generate all possible subarrays.",
    "betterSolution": "A more efficient solution can be achieved by utilizing a hashmap to store cumulative sums encountered so far and their frequencies. This allows for constant time lookups, reducing the overall time complexity.",
    "optimalSolution": "The optimal solution involves iterating through the array, maintaining a cumulative sum, and utilizing a hashmap to store the cumulative sum and its frequency. For each cumulative sum, it checks if the difference between the current cumulative sum and the target sum k exists in the hashmap. If it does, it increments the count by the frequency of this difference, as each occurrence represents a subarray with the sum k.",
    "proofOfCorrectness": "The correctness of the optimal solution can be proven by recognizing that the cumulative sum at any index represents the sum of all elements up to that index. By storing these cumulative sums and their frequencies, we can efficiently identify all subarrays with sums equal to the target value k by checking for the existence of the difference between the current cumulative sum and k in the hashmap.",
